{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 09:01:56.260668", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- IP connectivity and routing across the enterprise look healthy (OSPF adjacencies and routes present; pings between hosts and server farm subnets succeed with low latency).\\n- The DNS service on the designated DNS server (10.200.0.2) is down. Clients cannot resolve service names (e.g., web0.local…web3.local, web99.local) despite reachability to the DNS host at the IP layer.\\n- The HTTP load balancer at 10.200.0.7 (nginx) is up and returns HTTP 200 via IP, and upstreams are configured on an internal backend network (20.200.0.0/24), consistent with the design to hide backends from user subnets.\\n\\nDetailed findings\\n\\n1) Reachability and routing health (normal)\\n- End-to-end ping tests:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 (dns_server): 0% loss, rtt ~2.4 ms\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6 (web_server_0..3): 0% loss, rtt ~2–3.6 ms\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2/0.5: 0% loss\\n  - Server farm internal pings between servers: 0% loss\\n- OSPF routes observed across routers:\\n  - server_access_router advertises 10.200.0.0/24 as connected and has OSPF routes to 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 via core.\\n  - core and distribution routers show consistent OSPF learned paths to 10.1.1.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, and 10.200.0.0/24 with reasonable metrics. No missing or flapping routes observed in the snapshots.\\n- Conclusion: Layer-3 routing is converged and healthy. No path loss detected.\\n\\n2) DNS service anomaly (abnormal)\\n- Client-side DNS configuration:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 resolv.conf points to nameserver 10.200.0.2.\\n- DNS resolution behavior from host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - getent hosts web99.local/web[0-3].local returns nothing (no resolution).\\n  - dig +short against 10.200.0.2 for the same names fails with “connection refused; no servers could be reached.”\\n  - TCP/UDP connectivity test: nc -zv 10.200.0.2 53 returns rc:1 (not listening/blocked).\\n- DNS server state (dns_server):\\n  - netstat -tuln shows no process listening on port 53.\\n  - named.service (BIND) is inactive (dead).\\n  - bind9.service is inactive (dead).\\n  - No alternative DNS daemon (e.g., dnsmasq) active.\\n- Impact:\\n  - Name-based access to services (web0.local…web3.local, web99.local) fails from user hosts, despite IP connectivity working.\\n- Root cause:\\n  - Application/service-layer failure on dns_server: DNS daemon is not running, port 53 closed, causing DNS queries to be refused.\\n\\n3) HTTP/load balancer and server farm (normal)\\n- Load balancer host (10.200.0.7):\\n  - Interfaces: eth0 10.200.0.7/24, eth1 20.200.0.1/24 (internal backend segment).\\n  - nginx service: Active (running).\\n  - Upstream config:\\n    - upstream web99 includes 20.200.0.2:80, 20.200.0.3:80, 20.200.0.4:80 (internal backend network, not advertised to users).\\n  - Client test:\\n    - host_1_1_1_1 -> http://10.200.0.7 returns HTTP 200 with subsecond total time.\\n- Web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6):\\n  - netstat shows TCP 0.0.0.0:80 listening on web_server_0..3.\\n  - Direct HTTP fetches by IP are responsive (based on curl timing and ping).\\n- Design alignment:\\n  - Back-end servers on 20.200.0.0/24 are not directly reachable from user hosts, consistent with the requirement that backends remain hidden. The public web servers in 10.200.0.0/24 are reachable (by IP), and the LB works via IP.\\n\\nLocalization of fault\\n- Faulty device: dns_server (10.200.0.2).\\n- Fault domain: Application/service layer on the DNS server (DNS daemon not running; port 53 closed).\\n- Network path and routing: Not implicated; connectivity to 10.200.0.2 is fine.\\n\\nSummary\\n- Abnormal behavior detected: DNS service outage on dns_server prevents hostname resolution across the network.\\n- All other core services validated:\\n  - OSPF routing tables consistent across core, distribution, and server access routers.\\n  - HTTP load balancer operational via IP; web servers listening and reachable via IP.\\n- Root cause: DNS daemon on dns_server is inactive (no listener on 53), leading to connection refused responses and name resolution failures, despite intact IP connectivity., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='cc2b771c-e545-4a17-b3ae-cdade234bbdc'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
